{"query": "What are the most beneficial tillage practices for increasing soil organic matter in arable fields on Mediterranean farmland?", "summary": "Based on multiple studies conducted in Mediterranean countries and similar climates, the most beneficial tillage practices for increasing soil organic matter in arable fields include reduced tillage and no-tillage systems. A meta-analysis from multiple Mediterranean countries found that both reduced tillage and no-tillage systems consistently increased soil organic matter compared to conventional tillage. Specifically, 14 studies found more organic matter in soils with reduced tillage versus conventional tillage, while a meta-analysis and 14 additional studies found more organic matter in no-tillage soils compared to tilled soils.

Conservation tillage practices are most effective when combined with crop residue retention and cover cropping. Retaining crop residues on fields was shown to increase soil organic carbon and nitrogen levels in multiple studies from Australia and China. Growing winter cover crops in arable fields significantly increased soil organic matter (measured as carbon) in Mediterranean-type climates, with a meta-analysis and ten controlled studies from Italy, Spain, and the USA demonstrating consistent benefits.

The research indicates that the combination of no-tillage or reduced tillage with residue retention and cover crops creates optimal conditions for soil organic matter accumulation. These practices work synergistically to reduce soil erosion, improve soil aggregation, and enhance microbial biomass. Implementation should be long-term, as studies showed higher soil quality and greater organic matter accumulation in plots with long-term conservation tillage compared to short-term implementations.", "action_ids": ["1371", "1369", "1370", "906", "907", "1345", "897", "910"]}

