  "relevant_summary": "Cover crops in Mediterranean climates show complex trade-offs between crop yield and water availability. Regarding crop yield, the evidence from Spain and Italy shows mixed results: six studies found lower cash crop yields with winter cover crops compared to plots without them, while three studies found higher yields, eight studies showed inconsistent differences (sometimes higher, sometimes lower), and seven studies found no yield differences. The yield impacts varied by cover crop type, with legumes generally providing better outcomes than non-legumes.\n\nFor water availability, the evidence reveals several trade-offs: seven studies found less water in soils with winter cover crops, while two found more water in some comparisons. However, five studies found that less water was lost through drainage, runoff, or evaporation from plots with cover crops. Two Spanish studies showed conflicting results on water use - one found cover crops used more water than bare fallows, while another found no difference. The water content effects also varied with implementation, as Spanish studies found more water in soils with long-term versus short-term cover crops, and differences in water availability between different cover crop types.\n\nAdditional Mediterranean-specific findings include reduced nitrate leaching in Spanish studies with cover crops, and implementation options matter significantly - legume cover crops generally performed better for both yield and water conservation outcomes compared to non-legumes.",
